\Cref{fig:source-verse-expr} gives the syntax of Source Verse.
\Cref{fig:sv-to-sv-1} and \Cref{fig:sv-to-sv-2} rewrite Source Version
into Small Source Verse, whose syntax is given in \Cref{fig:small-source-verse}.
Small Source Verse is a subset of Source Verse, which is why we us the same non-terminals
for terms |t| in both.

\subsection{Missing features}
There are still many language features missing from the desugaring.
\begin{itemize}
\item Paths.  New primitive type.
\item More numeric types: |rational|, |float|, ...
\item Maps (i.e., finite mappings from values to values).
\item Loop construct, |loop|.
\item Imperative features.  These desugar into pointer manipulation:
  \begin{itemize}
  \item |var| create an assignable variable
  \item |set| set an assignable variable
  \item |alias|
  \item |ref|
  \end{itemize}
\item Records. |struct| desugars into a mapping from paths to values.
\item Object oriented features. |class| desugars similarely to |struct|, but with inheritance.
\item Enumeration types.
\item Union types.
\item Concurrency operations: |race|, |rush|, |sync|, |branch|, |spawn|.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Small Source Verse}

\Cref{fig:small-source-verse} gives the syntax of Small Source Verse.  Things to note:
\begin{itemize}
\item \emph{Scoping.}
  In Small Source Verse, a variable is brought into scope by |x := t|.  The scope of
  the binding depends on the \emph{innermost} scope-limiting construct:
  \begin{center}
    \begin{tabular}{ll}
      Innermost scope-limiting & Scope of |x| \\
      construct in which |x:=t| appears \\
      \hline
      Arm of a choice |t_1 `choice` t_2| & The entire arm \\
      Body of a |functionKW| & The entire body \\
      Scrutinee of an |if| & The scrutinee and |then| branch \\
      |then| or |else| branch of an |if| & That whole branch \\
      First argument of |for| & Both arguments of the |for| \\
      Second argument of |for| & That whole argument \\
    \end{tabular}
    \end{center}

\item Anonymous lambdas take the form |function((t))b|, where, unusually for a programming language, the
  ``bound variable'' is an arbitrary term |t_1|.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Source Verse: preliminaries}

\Cref{fig:source-verse-expr} gives the syntax of Source Verse.  Several things worth noting:
\begin{itemize}
  \item Source Verse uses the same scoping rules as Small Source Verse (\Cref{sec:small-source-verse}),
extended to account for the fact that \emph{patterns} bring variables into scope. \simon{Do we need to spell this out?}
\item Real Source Verse uses the keyword \textbf{function}, but in this document we use |functionKW| to make our examples fit
  on the page more easily.
  Simlarly real Source Verse uses |array t|, but we use |ar t| here.
\item Source Verse has constructs |block t| and |let (t) in t|, which
  are scope-limiting constructs.  We omit them to save clutter in Small Source Verse and Big Core Verse; in
  a program without shadowing they serve no useful purpose.
\end{itemize}

\Cref{fig:sv-to-sv-1} and \Cref{fig:sv-to-sv-2} rewrite Source Version
into Small Source Verse.  These rewrite rules should be repeatedly applied until none
are applicable; at that point the program will be in the Small Source Verse subset.

Much of this source-to-source rewriting simply removes simple syntactic sugar or
notational abbreviations.
For example:
\begin{itemize}
\item |()| is short for |array ()|
\item The lambda notation |t_1 eqgt t_2| is short for |functionP t_1 t_2|.
\item A multi-argument lambda |function (a_1 dots a_n) b| is short for the explicitly-curried \\
      |function a_1 (function a_2 (dots {function a_n b}))|.
\end{itemize}
\noindent

\subsection{Rewriting Source Verse patterns}

Source Verse has bindings |p := t|, where |p| is a \emph{pattern}.
These patterns are completely removed by the source-to-source rewrites in \Cref{fig:sv-to-sv-1},
yielding Small Source Verse bindings of the form |x := t|, or |x squiggt y := t| where |x|,|y| are variables.

Source Verse also has the term |p:t|, which immediately rewrites to |p := (:t)|.

\simon{Questions that Lennart and I tripped over}
Consider |((x:int):nat) := t_1| and |((y:nat):int) := t_2| .  Are these legal at all?
Can you have a |(x:int)| to the left of a colon?

If so, they desugar using \rulename{pcolonb} twice to
\begin{itemize}
  \item $ |((x:int):nat) := t_1| \longrightarrow  |x := oftype (oftype t_1 nat) int|$
  \item $ |((y:nat):int) := t_2| \longrightarrow  |y := oftype (oftype t_2 int) nat|$
\end{itemize}
So |(x:t_1):t_2| means the same as |x : (t_1 . t_2)|, where |.| is function composition. \simon{How do you write function composition in Verse?}\lennart{There is no operator for function composition.}


Now consider the terms |((x:int):nat)| and |((y:nat):int)| .  Again, are these legal at all?  They desugar strangely.  Consdier
the first.  It desugars using \rulename{pcolont} to |(x:int) := (:nat)|, and then by \rulename{pcolonb} to |x := oftype (:nat) int|.
It is strange that we use two different rules, with two different constructs on the RHS, to build the result.
Is this what we want?

We wondered about replacing \rulename{pcolont} with
$$
\rulename{pcolont'} \quad |p : t| \longrightarrow |(p:t) := (:any)|
$$
\simon{End of questions}

\subsection{Array splicing}
In an array expression, i.e., in the elements of |array| or comma separated elements,
a special syntactic form |..x| is allowed.  It indicates an \emph{array slice}, and it has its own desugaring rules,
\cref{fig:sv-to-sv-1}.

Here are a few examples to illustrate how it can be used.
The |append| function takes two array arguments and returns the appended arrays.
The |append| function is reversible so it can be used with uninstantiated logical variables as inputs.
The |append| function as been abbreviated to |app| and |array()| to |ar()|.

{\small
$$
\begin{array}{rclcl}
  \text{Source Verse}  & & \text{Small Source Verse} & & \text{Evaluates to} \\
  \hline
  |(1,..(2,3))|  & \longrightarrow & |app^[ar(1),ar(2;3)]| & \rightarrow & |ar(1;2;3)| \\
  |(..(1,2),3)|  & \longrightarrow & |app^[ar(1;2),ar(3)]| & \rightarrow & |ar(1;2;3)| \\
  |(x,..y)==(1,2,3)| & \longrightarrow & |app^[ar(x),y]==ar(1;2;3)| & \rightarrow &|x=1; y=ar(2;3)|\\
  |(1,..y)==(1,2,3)| & \longrightarrow & |app^[ar(1),y]==ar(1;2;3)| & \rightarrow &|y=ar(2;3)|\\
  |(5,..y)==(1,2,3)| & \longrightarrow & |app^[ar(5),y]==ar(1;2;3)| & \rightarrow &|fail|\\
  |(..x,..y)==ar(1)| & \longrightarrow & |app^[x,y]==ar(1)| & \rightarrow &|(x=ar();y=ar(1)) `choice` (x=ar(1); y=ar())|\\
\end{array}
$$
}

\subsection{Example rewriting}
$$
\begin{array}{lrcl}
  & \text{Source Verse}  & & \text{Small Source Verse} \\
  \hline
(E1) &  |x:int|  & \longrightarrow & |x := (:int)| \\
(E2) &  |x:abs := -3|  & \longrightarrow & |x := oftype (-3) abs| \\
(E3) &  |f^(x:int) := t| & \longrightarrow & |f := functionP(x := (:int)) (t)| \\
(E4) &  |f^(x:int):int := t| & \longrightarrow & |f := functionP(x := (:int)) (oftype t int)| \\
\end{array}
$$
Notice that
\begin{itemize}
\item The term |(:t)| in Small Source Verse, pronounced ``range |t|'' or ``colon |t|'',
  denotes the (possibly-infinite)
  set of all values in the range of the function\footnote{Remember, in Verse types are simply functions.} |t|.
  So in example (E1), (|x:int|) brings |x| into scope and
  constrains its value to be among those in the range of the function |int|; that is, to be an integer.
\item In Small Source Verse, the term |oftype t_1 t_2|, pronounced ``|t_1| has type |t_2|''
  means roughly\footnote{More precisely, this is its \emph{execution semantics}; its \emph{verification semantics}
  is slightly different; see \Cref{sec:verification}} |t_2^[t_1]|;
  that is, the result
  of applying the type |t_2| to |t_1|. So in example (E2), |(x:abs := -3)| rewrites to |(x := oftype(-3)abs)|, which later desugars to |x := abs^[-3]|, thereby binding |x| to |3|.  Note that the value of the original right-hand
  side (namely |-3|) is thereby ``fed through'' the type |abs| to give the value of |x|.
\item An argument |a| is a \emph{term} not a \emph{pattern}.
  In (E3), for example, the argument |(x:int)| rewrites (by \rulename{pcolont}) to |(x := (:int))|.
  In |functionP t_1 t_2| the argument (term) |t_1| is called the \emph{domain expression} of the function.
\end{itemize}

