\section{Desugaring Small Source Verse into Big Core Verse}

\Cref{fig:core-verse} gives the Big Core Verse language into which we desugar.
while \Cref{fig:desugar-expr1} desugars Small Source Verse into Big Core Verse.

\subsection{Big Core Verse}

Big Core Verse is slightly larger than the core language of the ICFP 23 paper, but
can very easily be desugared into it.  Specifically:
\begin{itemize}
\item It includes |x := e|.  This means |x=e|, plus an existential for |x| added at the
  top of the enclosing scope.
\item In |if (e_1) then e_2 else e_3| each of the |e_i| has its own scope, but existentials
  at the top of |e_1| also scope over |e_2|.  So |if (x:=f^[0]) { y:=x+1; y*y } else 0| gets turned into
  |if (def x (x==f^[0])) then (def y (y==x+1; y*y)) else 0|.
\item In |for (e_1) {e_2}| both expressions have their own scope, but with top existential in |e_1| scoping over |e_2|.
\end{itemize}


\subsection{Desugaring from source to core}

In desugaring from Source Verse into Core Verse, there are two big features to watch:
\begin{description}
\item[Functions.] We desugar Verse's lambdas |functionP t_1 t_2|, which (very unusually) have a domain \emph{expression} |t_1| rather
  than a (conventional) domain \emph{variable}.
\item[Verification.] We desugar certain constructs in two different ways, one for \emph{execution} and one for \emph{verification}.
\end{description}
\noindent


\subsubsection{Desugaring functions for execution}

We concentrate first on desugaring functions for execution.

Consider the Source Verse lambda |functionP 3 t|. This is a function that takes an
argument |i|\footnote{The name ``|i|'' connotes ``input''}, checks that it is
equal to 3 (failing
(\lennart{A closed function (application) fails at runtime.  An open function (application) fails at verification time,})
if not), and returns |t|.  So this Big Core term does the job: |lam i (i=3; t)|.
This desugaring works fine if the argument is an otherwise-unconstrained unification variable.
For example, consider this code:
$$
|x:int; f := functionP 3 99; f^[x]; x|
$$
The call |f^[x]| will constrain |x| to be |3|, so the expression returns |3|.

Now consider |x:=3; functionP x t|.  Here the |x| in |functionP x t| is an \emph{occurrence} of the |x|
bound by |x:=3|; it is \emph{not} a binding of |x|.  So
$$
|x:=3; functionP x t|  \quad\quad \text{desugars to} \quad\quad |x:=3; (lam i (i=x; t))|
$$
which (since we can substitute for |x|) means the same as the previous term.

Next, consider |functionP (3 `choice` 4) t|.  Just as before, this desugars to |lam i (i=(3 `choice` 4); t)|,
a function returns |t| if called with |3| or |4|, and fails otherwise.
So it is begining to look as if the general rule is:
$$
|functionP t_1 t_2|  \quad\quad \text{desugars to (not right yet)} \quad\quad |lam i (i=t_1; t_2)|
$$
That is the right idea, but we need more.  In particular, how \emph{can} we bind parameters?
Consider |function(x:int) t|.  We might imagine that
$$
|functionP (x:int) t|  \quad\quad \text{desugars to} \quad\quad |lam i (x := i; int^[x]; t)|
$$
The idea is that the |int^[x]| checks that |x| is indeed an |int|.  But in Verse a ``type''
is an arbitraray function, not necessarily an \emph{identity} function.
Consider the Source Verse lambda |function ((x:abs)) t|.  Then it would be wrong to say
$$
|functionP (x:abs) t|  \quad\quad \text{desugars to (wrong)} \quad\quad |lam i (x := i; abs^[x]; t)|
$$
because we want to feed the input |i| \emph{through} |abs|, like this:
$$
|functionP (x:abs) t|  \quad\quad \text{desugars to} \quad\quad |lam i (x := abs^[i]; t)|
$$
That is, the function takes an input argument |i|, applies the type |abs| to it
(which might fail), binds |x| to the result of |abs^[i]|, and evaluates |t| with that value of |x|.

In Small Source Verse |(functionP (x:abs) t)| rewrites to |functionP (x := :abs) t|.
So, given an input variable |i|, we want to desugar the domain expression |(x := :abs)| in such
a way that we feed |i| through |abs| to give the value of |x|.
In general, for a domain expression |t_1| we say that we want to \emph{match |t_1| against |i|};
we write |Me i t_1|, and its rules are given in \Cref{fig:desugar-match}.  Now we can desugar a function
as follows
$$
|functionP t_1 t_2|  \quad\quad \text \quad\quad |lam i (Me i t_1; t_2)|
$$
(Note: we say ``desugars to'' here, rather than citing a desugaring rule because it still
is not the whole story.  But it is close, and gives an accurate intuition for |(Me i t)|.)
This matching process is very like unification |(i = t_1)|, except for the single rule \rulename{mtype}.
\emph{This one rule is the entire difference between ``matching'' and regular unification.}
All the other rules exist only to make this one work. Let us see what happens for our example
|functionP (x := :abs) t|:
$$
\begin{array}{lll}
  |functionP (x := :abs) t| & \rightarrow \text{``desugars to''} & |lam i (Me i (x := :abs); t| \\
  & \rightarrow \{\rulename{mbind}\} & |lam i (x := Me i (:abs)); t| \\
  & \rightarrow \{\rulename{mtype}\} & |lam i (x := abs^[i]; t)|
\end{array}
$$
Here you can see \rulename{mtype} in action.

