\subsection{The pattern |y squiggt x|}

What does the strange pattern |y squiggt x| do?  As you can see from rule \rulename{msquig}, it
allows you access to the \emph{input} of the match as well as the \emph{output}.  So in
$$
|f( (y squiggt x) : abs ) := dots|
$$
in a call |f(-4)|, |x| gets bound to |4|, but |y| gets bound to the original input, |(-4)|.

This is useful for arrays.  Suppose |a| is an array.  Consider the Source Verse terms
|x:a| and |x := :a|.
The two are equivalent; remember rule \rulename{pcolont}.
Both use |a| as a type, but arrays are functions, so that's fine. \simon{Its not an idempotent function though!
  Here we are usefully using a non-idempotent function as a ``type''.}\lennart{I think it's worth pointing out that
  types are idempotent functions, but the the |t| in |:t| does not have to be a type.  It can be any function.}
Then |(x := :a)| desugars (via \rulename{dexpr} and \rulename{mtype}) to |x := def i (a^[i])|.
Then our execution semantics for arrays rewrites thus:
$$
|a^[i]| \longrightarrow |(i=0; v_1) `choice` dots `choice` (i=n; v_n)|
$$
where the elements of |a| are |v_0, dots, v_n|.  So the net effect is that |x:a| binds |x| successively
to the elements of |a|; it is an implicit for-loop.
We can use |for| to build a new array; thus |for(x:a){x+1}| returns an array the same size as |a| but
with each element increased by 1.

Now consider |(i squiggt x):a|.  That binds |i| and |x| successively to the \emph{index/value} pairs of |a|.
How does that happen?  Consider
$$
\begin{array}{ll}
  |De ((i squiggt x) := :a)| \\
  \rightarrow \{\rulename{dexpr}\} &
    |def j (Me j ((i squiggt x) := :a))| \\
  \rightarrow \{\rulename{msquig}\} &
    |def j (x := (Me j (:a)); i := j| \\
  \rightarrow \{\rulename{mtype}\} &
    |def j (x := a^[j]; i := j| \\
  \rightarrow \{\text{bind |x| and |i| and rewrite}\} &
  |def (i x) (dots (x = a^[i]) dots)|
\end{array}
$$
Clever!  Incidentally, from \rulename{msquig} you can see that the form |x := t| is redundant
in the syntax of Small Source Verse.
We could just have |(y squiggt x) := t| with a fresh |y|.  But the for |x := t| is so
ubiquitously useful that we include it in our syntax.

